/* Dashboard dark mode support
 * ===========================
 *
 * This is a mild hack that overrides the default FUI element styles with the
 * inverted variant styles when we detect the user is using the dark theme.
 * The end result is that the inverted element styles can overlay the existing
 * element styles using a media query and without altering template HTML with
 * all of the extra inverted classes.
 *
 * There are two caveats below to this method and both are due to how LESS works.
 *
 * Using the dark mode CSS
 * -----------------------
 *
 * The first caveat is that we can't use LESS `extend()` with LESS media queries
 * because of how it handles scoping inside media queries -- these have local
 * scope with no access to global scope.
 *
 * So, the following does not work and will output * nothing, because
 * `.ui.inverted.label` does not exist in the local scope of the `@media` rule:
 *
 * .. code:: less
 *
 *     @media ... {
 *       .ui.label :extend(.ui.inverted.label) {};
 *     }
 *
 * So instead, we output the dark mode alterations as a separate CSS file and
 * include it using link element with media attributes to active the media query:
 *
 * .. code:: html
 *
 *     <link rel="stylesheet" href="site.css" media="all" />
 *     <link rel="stylesheet" href="dark.css" media="{{ if use_dark_theme|yesno:"all,(prefers-color-scheme: dark)" }}" />
 *
 * The conditional media query rule attribute is what activates dark mode on
 * `dark` theme and on `system` theme when the preferred color scheme is dark.
 *
 * Updating rules
 * --------------
 *
 * The second caveat is that LESS requires us to extend rules individually. This
 * means it isn't possible to extend with just `extend(.ui.inverted.button)`
 * and get all of the related rules, we must also extend rules like
 * `extend(.ui.inverted.button:hover)` and so on.
 *
 * All of the selectors below were pulled from the compiled site CSS and copied
 * here. The aim is to extend any rule that has a selector for inverted styles
 * (eg `.ui.inverted.label`) and override the matching non-inverted selector
 * (eg `.ui.label`) when dark mode is enabled.
 *
 * There are a lot of rules below, but the process to build this list is
 * reproducible. The basic approach is:
 *
 * - Filter the compiled site CSS to gather the actual rule selectors we want to
 *   extend:
 *
 * .. code:: console
 *
 *     prettier --parser css < readthedocsext/theme/static/readthedocsext/theme/css/site.css | grep '.inverted'
 *
 * - From here, to fix a particular style issue, search this list of selctors
 *   for a rule that matches and is missing below.
 * - Selectors using features like `:not()` or `:has()` can't be extended yet.
 *   These can be skipped for now.
 * - Transform the selectors to match the rules below, extend from the inverted
 *   style selector to the non-inverted selector (mostly just remove
 *   `.inverted` from the selectors).
 * - Ordering is important still, or use specificity to control the rule order.
 * - Lastly, there are a few overrides where we want extend alternate styles,
 *   these have special rules and are noted below -- eg `.ui.label` extends
 *   `.ui.basic.inverted.label`, not `.ui.inverted.label`.
 */
html[data-theme="dark"]:not(#_) .ui.button,
